## 8. Pattern/Structure Used for All Template Handlers

### Legacy Handlers (src/llama-chat.cpp):
- **Switch-based dispatch** on enum value
- **Iterates through messages**, applying role/content formatting
- **Manually constructs strings** with special tokens
- **Pattern**: Role markers + content + separators
- **Examples**:
  - ChatML: `<|im_start|>{role}\n{content}<|im_end|>\n`
  - Llama2: `[INST]{content}[/INST]` with `<<SYS>>{system}<</SYS>>` wrapper
  - Mistral V3: `[INST]{content}[/INST]{response}</s>`

### Modern Handlers (common/chat.cpp):
- **Jinja2 template-based** rendering with context variables
- **Capability detection** (supports_tool_calls, supports_system_role, etc.)
- **JSON-to-context conversion** for flexible message passing
- **Specialized handlers** for models with unique parsing requirements
- **PEG parser generation** for structured output parsing

---

## 9. Key Markers & Detection Strings

**Mistral-specific markers:**
- `[INST]` / `[/INST]` - User instruction markers (V1, V3, Llama2)
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` / `[/SYSTEM_PROMPT]` - System message (V7)
- `[TOOL_CALLS]` - Tool invocation marker (Ministral-3)
- `[ARGS]` - Tool arguments marker (Ministral-3)
- `[THINK]` / `[/THINK]` - Reasoning markers (Ministral-3)
- `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` - Tool availability marker (V3)
- `[CALL_ID]` - Distinguishes Mistral Small 3.2 from Ministral

**Detection heuristics:**
- `"mistral"` at start of template name
- `[INST]` markers presence
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (V7 specific)
- `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` (V3/V1 specific)
- Space/no-space before `[INST]` distinguishes V1 from V3
- Quote style around `[INST]` distinguishes V3-Tekken

